Management of hyperparathyroidism

  • Primary hyperparathyroidism: The only definitive treatment is parathyroidectomy.
    • Indications for surgery:
      • Symptomatic patient
      • Renal stones
      • Osteoporosis
      • Age < 50
      • eGFR < 60
      • Calcium >= 0.25 mmol above ULN.

Albright's hereditary osteodystrophy (AHO) is a characteristic skeletal phenotype, including short stature, obesity, round face, and brachydactyly. AHO appears in patients with pseudohypoparathyroidism (PHP) who have resistance to PTH and in their eumetabolic family members who have pseudopseudohypoparathyroidism (PPHP).

[!TIP] Shortcuts for remembering visual field defects.
Lesions anterior to the chiasma cause ipsilateral ('uni-ocular') defects.
Any lesion posterior to the chiasma causes a contralateral homonymous defect.
